The Lee County Eagle Tree located in front of the Old Lee County Courthouse on Main Street in downtown Fort Myers was removed recently. Lee County’s Department of Facilities, Construction & Management is renovating the Eagle Tree to preserve and protect it from environmental impacts. The renovations will be completed off site at a Lee County facility. Project completion is expected within about six months. The tree, which dates back to around 1900, has been a sculpture since 2011.
Credit/Source: Kinfay Moroti / The News-Press USA TODAY NETWORK - FLORIDA

Caption: Marjory Stoneman Douglas High School senior Mei-Ling Ho Shing, 17, rehearses a lyrical praise dance at the Village United Methodist Church in North Lauderdale on Tuesday, Feb. 5, 2019. She was in the building where 17 people were shot and killed at the school Feb. 14, 2018. A year later she is struggling with the aftermath but has also stepped forward as an activist and voice against gun violence in minority communities among other things. She plans on honoring the victims of the shooting with the dance. (Photo: Andrew West, Fort Myers News-Press USA TODAY NETWORK- FLORIDA)

Caption: The guest home is nicknamed the "spider" because of the beams that were built off the home to hold the weights for the shutters. The Walker guest home and main home on Sanibel. The Walker guest house was designed by architect Paul Rudolph. The Cottage is considered the pedigree of mid-century modernism and was recognized by AIA Florida Chapter's Best Residential Building in the State of Florida. Also known as the "Cannonball House" and "Spider" because of the red cannonballs Rudolph used as weights to  hold the signature wood shutters in place.  (Photo: Andrea Melendez/The News-Press/USA Today)

Also known as the "Cannonball House" and "Spider" because of the red cannonballs Rudolph used as weights to  hold the signature wood shutters in place.

Caption: Ramona Miller makes phone calls to detox centers for Jessica Weatherley and her on again off again boyfriend Brian Cooper. They had no luck finding a center that would take them because they donÕt have insurance and Weatherley wanted to go together with Cooper.  (Photo: Andrew West/The News-Press)
The Weatherley sisters of Fort Myers, Jessica (left) and Willie, before Jessica's death in December, 2018. (Photo: Courtesy Willie Weatherley)

Jessica Weatherley speaks with caseworker Ramona Miller in the parking lot of a restuarant along U.S. 41 in early November of 2018. Weatherley struggled with a fentanyl addiction and passed away a week before Christmas of 2018.  (Photo: Andrew West/The News-Press)

Willie Weatherley, left,  pleads with he sister, Jessica Weatherley to enter a detox center on Monday 11/12/2018. Weatherley and her on again off again boyfriend, Brian Cooper are addicted to Fentanyl. They had made a call to Ramona Miller to get into detox, but over a course of several hours and calls to detox centers with no availability or to many obstacles tehy couldnÕt overcome,  they decided to hit the streets again.  (Photo: Andrew West/The News-Press)

Hand-holding opioid addicts after they're released from detox to help them stick with a treatment program really works, data from Central Florida Behavioral Health Network shows. Unfortunately, there's not enough money to do it for everyone. (Photo: Central Florida Behavioral Health Network)

Ramona Miller of A Voice in the Wilderness coaxes Stephen Kurzyna, a heroin user  and self admitted dealer, to get help in a San Carlos convenience store parking lot. Kurzyna, who relapsed last year, insisted he is not ready to stop using.

Ana Novicki,22, prepares to inject fetanyl in a North Fort Myers motel room. She shot opioids for the first time when she was 17. She remembers feeling the addiction take hold in the first rush of injecting the hard drug.

Stephen Kurzyna suffers the physical effects of what he calls Òdope sicknessÓ as he meets with Ramona Miller of A Voice in the Wilderness. Miller offers to take him to detox or a treatment center. On this night he refuses.

In a screen grab from video, Lucy Tapia, 25, gives a mock demonstration of administering Narcan nasal spray to Stephen Kurzyna, 32, in San Carlos Park, after watching Ramona Miller of A Voice in the Wilderness do it. Tapia is a fentanyl user, while Kurzyna is a heroin user and self-admitted dealer. With help from the Department of Children and Families, Miller distributes the opioid overdose antidote directly to users on the streets of Southwest Florida and makes sure they know how to use it.
Boxes of Narcan, an overdose antidote sit near at hand in a North Fort Myers motel room where IV drug users are staying. The Narcan is provided to them by Ramona Miller of A Voice in the Wilderness.

Date: Published 11:00 a.m. ET Feb. 7, 2019 | Updated 5:22 p.m. ET Feb. 7, 2019
Caption: Chris Shin, Ember's general manager, shows how to cook on the in-table Korean barbecue grills. Ember Korean Steakhouse opened in mid-December in south Fort Myers. (Photo: Andrea Melendez/The News-Press/USA Today)
Ember Korean Steakhouse opened in mid-December in the former Stonewood Grill space on College Parkway in south Fort Myers. Get a behind-the-plates look at our food critic's review.

The King of the Sea roll from Ember Korean Steakhouse features tuna, avocado and cucumber inside, with lushly fatty slivers of toro (blue-fin tuna belly) layered over top. Ember's sushi program is outstanding, nailing everything from the warm stickiness of the rice to the cool-but-not-cold temperature of the fish.

Poutine, the Ember Steakhouse way, starts with hand-cut potatoes fried in beef tallow. Shreds of Korean brisket are layers over top along with cheese curds, pickled onions and a deliciously peppery gravy.
Hand-made mandu dumplings may be stuffed with kimchi, chicken or beef at Ember. They are roughly the size of a fist; huge and delicious.
A platter of meats and a beautiful mess of banchan (Korean side dishes) clutter an open-fire grill sizzling with Prime steaks at one of Ember's Korean barbecue tables.
Ember's servers must balance the mania of waiting on customers while also cooking their meals on in-table grills. To their credit: They're doing an excellent job.
Pan-roasted cauliflower slicked in gochujang butter and shaved grana padano from the lunch menu at Ember Korean Steakhouse.
Ember's "All About Seoul" cocktail is made with soju, Fino sherry, fresh lime and mint.
Ember Steakhouse's "Tuna In Love" roll is made with spicy tuna and cucumber inside, with avocado and more tuna over top.

Research at the UCLA Laboratory of Neuro Imaging conducted in 2004 by Dr. Paul Thompson shows that judgment is the last to develop. Time-lapse MRI (magnetic resonance imaging) images of normal brain development from the ages 5 and 20 shows the growth and gradual loss of gray matter, which contains cells that process information. (Red areas contain more gray matter, blue areas less.) At the start of puberty, a thinning of gray matter begins, which corresponds to increased cognitive abilities. As the brain pares back redundant connections, it increases the amount of white matter that helps cells communicate and improves the ability to regulate decision-making and emotional arousal.(Photo: Contributed image from Gogtay et al. (2004), PNAS)

Caption: This cosmetic surgery facility in suburban Miami has undergone name changes over the years, but one person has been at the center: Dr. Ismael Labrador. Tucked away in a strip mall between a barber shop and a discount shoe store, the facility carries out popular but risky procedures that have resulted in numerous deaths and injuries since 2013. (Photo: Dorothy Edwards/Naples Daily News)
Dr. Ismael Labrador (Photo: MIAMI-DADE POLICE DEPARTMENT)

Miami is a major center for troubled cosmetic surgery clinics -- driven by  discount prices and social media advertising -- where  doctors with little specialized training perform some of the riskiest procedures in plastic surgery. (Photo: Dorothy Edwards/Naples Daily News)

The sprawling country estate in Miami-Dade purchased in 2014 by Ismael Labrador, founder of a cosmetic surgery business that has experienced the highest number of patient deaths in Florida since 2013. (Photo: Dorothy Edwards/Naples Daily News)

The death of Heather Meadows, a 29-year-old mother of two from West Virginia, in 2016 prompted a state investigation that led to malpractice charges against her surgeon by the Florida health department. James McAdoo, who denied any wrongdoing, will appear before the state board of osteopathic medicine. (Photo: Submitted)

Biomedical waste containers in the parking area behind Jolie Plastic Surgery, where some patients are led into waiting taxis and ride services after surgeries. (Photo: Dorothy Edwards/Naples Daily News)

Tammy Meadows says the death of her daughter, Heather Meadows, 29, from complications of her cosmetic surgery in Miami in 2016, has been especially difficult for her son Malakhi, 8. "When she died, a part of everyone else died," said Meadows. "It's just so hard." She and her husband, Reggie, are now raising their two grandchildren at the family home in Bluefield, WV. (Photo: Dorothy Edwards/Naples Daily News)

Florida resident Ivis Beracierto, 48, said she was not properly treated for pain and infected wounds after her cosmetic surgery at the Hialeah clinic in 2016. So she went to a local emergency room, where doctors found gangrene had spread through her abdomen, medical records show. (Photo: Dorothy Edwards/Naples Daily News)

Tammy Meadows now cares for her daughter's two children, Maliya, 2, and Malakhi, 8, in her West Virginia home after her daughter died from complications of cosmetic surgery at a troubled Hialeah, FL, clinic. Heather Meadows, a 29-year-old single mother, was among eight women who died after procedures at the plastic surgery business founded by Dr. Ismael Labrador. (Photo: Dorothy Edwards/Naples Daily News)

Suzanna Wilson hugs the young daughter of her best friend, Heather Meadows, 29, who died after cosmetic surgery at a Hialeah, FL, clinic in 2016. Wilson said she texted her friend just minutes before she underwent surgery. "Her last words to me was, 'I love you,''' she said. "I told her that I loved her, too." (Photo: Dorothy Edwards/Naples Daily News)

Three giant fish flopped out of the truck onto the ground from this load that was brought from a few of the beaches on Sanibel Island. The amounts of fish and ocean creatures being brought in are slowing down, but the beaches are still being cleaned up. The county and islands have collected millions of pounds of fish and sea creatures after a large Red Tide outbreak. Where does it go in the end? The landfill. Once the ocean creatures are collected from the beaches, they are brought to the landfill, mixed with other trash, and then burned.

Caption: Gulf shrimp in a Moroccan spiced sauce from a recent specials menu at Malia Island Fusion. (Photo: Special to The News-Press)
Chicken wings in a sticky Thai glaze ($12) are finished with chopped macadamia nuts, cilantro and a crunchy slaw at Malia Island Fusion. (Photo: Special to The News-Press)
Malia serves its Iberico pork loin ($38) over creamy gigante beans with hunks of pork belly. A date-cream sauce finished the dish. (Photo: Special to The News-Press)

The Thai noodle salad is on the lunchtime menu at Malia Island Fusion on Sanibel. Shown here with salmon for $22, the dish starts at $14. While the salmon was perfect, the noodles (overdressed and salty) were a rare miss for the restaurant. But even Malia's misses look stunning.
Malia Island Fusion opened in the former Blue Coyote space on Sanibel in November 2018.
Gulf shrimp in a Moroccan spiced sauce from a recent specials menu at Malia Island Fusion.

Malia serves its Iberico pork loin ($38) over creamy gigante beans with hunks of pork belly. A date-cream sauce finished the dish. It's one of the best and most interesting things I've eaten in quite some time.
Chicken wings in a sticky Thai glaze ($12) are finished with chopped macadamia nuts, cilantro and a crunchy slaw at Malia Island Fusion.
Black garlic shrimp ($29) served with creamed corn, cumin-butter polenta, shishito peppers, charred sweet corn, queso fresco and a cilantro crema from Malia.
A simple but deeply flavorful bean soup ($8) from Malia Island Fusion.

Caption: This cosmetic surgery facility in suburban Miami has undergone name changes over the years, but one person has been at the center: Dr. Ismael Labrador. Tucked away in a strip mall between a barber shop and a discount shoe store, the facility carries out popular but risky procedures that have resulted in numerous deaths and injuries since 2013. (Photo: Dorothy Edwards/Naples Daily News)
Dr. Ismael Labrador (Photo: MIAMI-DADE POLICE DEPARTMENT)

Miami is a major center for troubled cosmetic surgery clinics -- driven by  discount prices and social media advertising -- where  doctors with little specialized training perform some of the riskiest procedures in plastic surgery. (Photo: Dorothy Edwards/Naples Daily News)

The sprawling country estate in Miami-Dade purchased in 2014 by Ismael Labrador, founder of a cosmetic surgery business that has experienced the highest number of patient deaths in Florida since 2013. (Photo: Dorothy Edwards/Naples Daily News)

The death of Heather Meadows, a 29-year-old mother of two from West Virginia, in 2016 prompted a state investigation that led to malpractice charges against her surgeon by the Florida health department. James McAdoo, who denied any wrongdoing, will appear before the state board of osteopathic medicine. (Photo: Submitted)

Biomedical waste containers in the parking area behind Jolie Plastic Surgery, where some patients are led into waiting taxis and ride services after surgeries. (Photo: Dorothy Edwards/Naples Daily News)

Tammy Meadows says the death of her daughter, Heather Meadows, 29, from complications of her cosmetic surgery in Miami in 2016, has been especially difficult for her son Malakhi, 8. "When she died, a part of everyone else died," said Meadows. "It's just so hard." She and her husband, Reggie, are now raising their two grandchildren at the family home in Bluefield, WV. (Photo: Dorothy Edwards/Naples Daily News)

Suzanna Wilson hugs the young daughter of her best friend, Heather Meadows, 29, who died after cosmetic surgery at a Hialeah, FL, clinic in 2016. Lakewood Postal on Indrio Road, seen July 31, 2017, is where the former Five Star Food Store was located in Lakewood Park. Tariq Hussain, of Vero Beach, was working a late shift at the family business in 1995 when he was shot and killed. Lanadieal Ashe, of Fort Pierce, who was a juvenile at the time, was convicted of his murder.(Photo: XAVIER MASCAREÑAS/TCPALM)

During a brief hearing on Thursday, March 29, 2018, St. Lucie Circuit Judge Gary Sweet threw out the life sentence Lanadieal Ashe began serving after being convicted of shooting Tariq Hussain Dec. 5, 1995. Now after more than 22 years in prison, Ashe, 39, was resentenced to a 40-year term.(Photo: PATRICK DOVE/TCPALM)

Aslam “Ozzie” Hussain, brother of slain convenience store owner Tariq Hussain, attended a resentencing hearing for convicted murderer Lanadieal Ashe on Monday, Dec. 18, 2017 at the St. Lucie County Courthouse in Fort Pierce.
